, Portugal":"Ribeira, Aveiro, Portugal","Portugal":"Portugal","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ribeira","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician and Portuguese: variant of <b>Ribeira</b>, a habitational name from any of numerous places called Ribeira, meaning ‘bank, shore’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Paio","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Francisco ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Moniz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Mario, Fernando, Hilario, Jorge, Rogerio, Adelino, Adriano, Alberto, Alfredo.  Portuguese Joao, Agostinho, Duarte, Guilherme, Henrique.","Portuguese: patronymic from the medieval personal name<i>Munho</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Muniz","meanings":["‘Luminous, bright, shining’."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Paio Moniz de Ribeira was born about 1140, in Ribeira, Aveiro, Portugal, his father, Munio Fromariques de Ribadouro, was 116 and his mother, Elvira Gondesendes, was 97. He married Doña Urraca Núñez de Bragança about 1160, in Por